11/03/2026 14:36:32 PM|Trace|Ghosts.Client.Handlers.OutlookHelper.Execute|Built email configuration from timeline {"Id":"6aa78959-a80a-475d-a1c8-bc0e81ac2941","From":"CurrentUser","To":["Leopoldo.Dubuque.mil@mail.mil","Wendie.Schiefelbein.civ@mail.mil"],"Cc":["William.Manion@generaldynamics.com"],"Bcc":["Kiyoko.Havens.mil@mail.mil","Ayako.Imler@l3t.com"],"Subject":"\"BRAZIL-\"","Body":"Brazil- FYI: Brazilian FM defends dialogue with  BRASILIA, Feb. 9 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Foreign Minister Celso Amorim said Tuesday Brazil would maintain negotiations with  on uranium enrichment and oppose any sanctions against . Amorim said Brazil was against the production of nuclear weapons, but  had the right to carry out a peaceful nuclear program. \"Dialogue is still possible. What we want is to make sure (that the uranium will not be used to make weapons) through peaceful ways and dialogue,\" Amorim told reporters. Under a draft deal brokered by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), the UN nuclear watchdog, most of 's existing low-grade enriched uranium should be shipped to  and France, where it would be processed into fuel rods with a purity of 20 percent.  declared on Tuesday it had started the process of producing 20-percent enriched uranium inside the country. In response to 's announcement, the U.S.-led Western countries have warned to take political and economic sanctions against . For his part, Amorim said he considered any kind of sanctions ineffective and dangerous because they might cross a limit and jeopardize peace. 's president made an official visit to Brazil in November, during which the Brazilian government defended 's right to have its own peaceful nuclear program including uranium enrichment similar to Brazil's, following international standards.V/r,\r\n\r\nCurrentUser\r\n\r\nCONFIDENTIALITY NOTICE: This e-mail message, including any attachments, may contain information that is protected by the DoD Privacy Act. This e-mail transmission is intended solely for the addressee(s). If you are not the intended recipient, you are hereby notified that you are not authorized to read, print, retain, copy, disclose, distribute, or use this message, any part of it, or any attachments. If you have received this message in error, please immediately notify the sender by telephone or return e-mail and delete this message and any attachments from your system without reading or saving in any manner. You can obtain additional information about the DoD Privacy Act at http://dpclo.defense.gov/privacy.\r\n\r\nTimestamp: Wednesday, 11 March 2026\r\nID: 6aa78959-a80a-475d-a1c8-bc0e81ac2941","Attachments":[],"BodyType":0}...
